<HEADLINE>
FT  09 FEB 94 / Brazilian spending fund approved
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANGUS FOSTER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   SAO PAULO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Brazil's Congress yesterday averted a clash with finance minister Fernando
Henrique Cardoso when it approved the first of two votes on an emergency
fund to help balance the government's budget.
Mr Cardoso, who had threatened to resign if the fund was defeated, finally
won Congress' support following last-minute concessions apparently designed
to limit education cuts. He is now expected to push ahead with the next
steps in his economic stabilisation programme, designed to tackle inflation
of more than 40 per cent a month.
The emergency fund is designed to give the government more control over
spending and raising new money. It will hold and directly distribute
spending which would normally be immediately transferred to states and
government agencies. By retaining these resources, the government will be
able to claim a balanced budget.
About Dollars 16bn of tax and social contributions will be channelled into
the fund, slightly more than was expected when Mr Cardoso announced his
package last year. He was forced to negotiate an increase in the fund after
Congress defeated a proposal for a slight increase in corporate tax.
Instead, the government will raise taxes and social contributions on banks
and retain federal employees' income tax now transferred to the states.
The fund is being set up through a constitutional amendment and therefore
requires a second vote.
</TEXT>
