<HEADLINE>
FT  09 FEB 94 / Court foils Fiat plans for lay-offs
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT GRAHAM
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   ROME
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Fiat's hopes of being able to push through a 5 per cent reduction in its
automotive workforce and lay off a further 10 per cent for two years have
received a setback from the courts.
A Milan court has ruled invalid a decision by Fiat to lay off for two years
some 2,000 workers and 239 white collar staff at the Arese plant of Alfa
Romeo near Milan. Fiat will therefore be obliged to bring these people back
on to the full payroll .
Unless the company can find a way round the ruling it could undermine the
Turin-based car group's plans to cut labour costs and return car-making
operations to profit.
The ruling followed legal action by the most militant trade union grouping,
Cobas, challenging the move which was put into effect three weeks ago. Arese
employed 9,000 people before the restructuring plan began to be implemented
and faces closure by 1996. The plant accounts for a quarter of the Fiat
group's total planned lay-offs and job cuts.
The court upheld Cobas's claim that the lay-offs broke an agreement between
management and unions made last June. This accepted the principle that
future lay-offs would not be for indeterminate periods and that laid-off
workers would be able to alternate with periods of work.
