<HEADLINE>
FT  09 FEB 94 / UN row over Bosnian air strikes: Russia and China lead
opposition to action against Serbs
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL LINDEMANN and AGENCIES
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Two of the five permanent members of the United Nations Security Council
yesterday came out against air strikes against the Bosnian Serbs, with
Russia claiming that the UN secretary-general, Mr Boutros Boutros Ghali, had
exceeded his authority in instructing Nato to prepare for such action.
China said it wanted to see only peaceful means used to settle the conflict
in Bosnia, instead of 'actions which might intensify the confrontation and
further complicate the situation there'. With Nato ambassadors due to
consider the feasibility of air strikes at a meeting in Brussels today, the
Russian foreign ministry yesterday issued a statement saying that 'Mr
Boutros Ghali's letter (to Nato) deals with actions which go beyond UN
resolutions on Bosnia'.
In the letter - delivered to Mr Manfred Worner, the Nato secretary-general,
on Sunday - Mr Boutros Ghali said he was empowered under UN resolution 836
to authorise the use of force in Bosnia.
However, Mr Mikhail Demurin, a Russian foreign ministry spokesman, said Mr
Boutros Ghali's request to Nato should have been made only after
consultations with the international community. 'Nato's readiness for
strikes is one thing, while making a political decision to launch them is
quite another,' he said.
Ukraine and Canada, which both have peacekeepers in former Yugoslavia,
yesterday spoke out against military intervention as well, fearing it might
endanger their troops.
The US also appeared to be retreating from the idea of air strikes. White
House spokeswoman Dee Dee Myers said the US was still focusing on diplomatic
remedies to the situation and would present 'ideas to reinvigorate the peace
process' at today's Nato meeting. On Monday, President Bill Clinton said he
supported Mr Boutros Ghali's request for Nato to prepare for air strikes.
However, the UK seemed to be softening its opposition to air strikes, in the
belief that there was likely to be overwhelming support for an ultimatum to
the Bosnian Serbs.
Mr John Major, the UK prime minister, renewed calls for urgent action as Mr
Malcolm Rifkind, the defence secretary, returned to London from Bosnia for
an emergency cabinet meeting on the matter. Mr Major emphasised that UN
forces must apply 'immediate and strong pressure' to halt attacks on
Sarajevo. He said UN commanders should set clear and specific conditions for
relief of the city.
Mr Major insisted, however, that the UK would continue to block any
suggestion of generalised air attacks, amid considerable doubts about the
likely effectiveness of such action.
Mr Mate Boban, the hardline nationalist leader of the Bosnian Croats,
resigned yesterday, an apparent casualty of growing international pressure
on his political backers in Croatia.
</TEXT>
