<HEADLINE>
FT  09 FEB 94 / Nato nears ultimatum to Serbs over siege of Sarajevo
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP STEPHENS, Political Editor
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Nato is expected today to agree on an ultimatum demanding that Bosnian Serb
forces withdraw from around Sarajevo and lift the siege of the city or face
western air strikes.
After intensive contacts yesterday which brought the 16 Nato allies close to
agreement, ambassadors of the alliance were expected at a meeting in
Brussels to approve formally a plan to give the besieging Serb forces a
limited time to withdraw.
The allies are responding to a request from Mr Boutros Boutros Ghali, UN
secretary-general, to prepare for air strikes against any artillery shelling
Sarajevo, following last week's marketplace mortar attack which killed 68
people.
The carnage pushed the west towards doing what it has threatened to do since
last August when Nato announced it was preparing air strikes against the
Bosnian Serbs if they continued their 'strangulation' of Sarajevo.
The French foreign minister, Mr Alain Juppe, said last night he believed
Nato ambassadors would endorse the ultimatum plan. 'I think we shall be able
to present a joint, especially French-US, position demanding the lifting of
the siege, that is to say the pull-back of besieging forces,' he told French
television. He warned that France might pull its peacekeepers out of Bosnia
if Nato backed down. 'France will not associate itself with a non-decision,'
he said.
However, the US placed new emphasis on the search for a diplomatic solution,
without ruling out the use of force. A White House official said a strategy
approved by President Bill Clinton would entail increased US representation
in the peace talks, but not to the point of putting 'undue pressure' on the
Bosnian government.
Mr Juppe said that under the proposal the Bosnian Serbs would be requested
to pull back 20-30km from the Bosnian capital and place all heavy weapons
within that area under UN control.
In London, an emergency meeting of senior UK ministers chaired by Mr John
Major, the prime minister, agreed to support an ultimatum. British officials
refused to discuss the details of such a warning ahead of today's Brussels
meeting.
Earlier Mr Major had indicated that Britain had softened its previous
opposition to air strikes when he told the House of Commons that the UN
forces must apply 'immediate and strong pressure' to halt attacks on
Sarajevo.
Any final Nato agreement on an ultimatum is likely to anger Russia. Moscow
opposes air strikes on the grounds that they would make the conflict worse,
but also has strong traditional links with the Serbs. The Russians have
accused Mr Boutros Ghali of exceeding his powers.
Mr Radovan Karadzic, the Bosnian Serb leader, said last night that any
aircraft attacking Serb forces would be shot down.
Doubts persist on Bosnia air strikes, Page 2
</TEXT>
