<HEADLINE>
FT  09 FEB 94 / GKN makes hostile Pounds 496m offer for Westland group
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By TIM BURT
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
GKN, the engineering and industrial services group, launched a hostile
Pounds 496m takeover bid yesterday for Westland, the helicopter manufacturer
at the centre of a cabinet crisis over its ownership eight years ago.
The bid was announced after GKN said it had agreed to acquire the 18.7 per
cent stake in Westland held by United Technologies (UTC), the US parent
company of Sikorsky helicopters.
The takeover would transform GKN - which already manufactures light armoured
vehicles - from a group dominated by automotive components and industrial
services into a company led by military sales.
Sir Leslie Fletcher, Westland chairman, was informed of the move in a dawn
telephone call yesterday from Sir David Lees, his GKN counterpart. Combined
with GKN's existing 28.3 per cent stake, the extra holding would give GKN 47
per cent of Westland on a fully converted basis.
Westland responded coolly, calling GKN's overture an 'unwelcome offer'. It
advised shareholders to take no action until it discussed the offer with
Schroders, its financial advisers.
The bid comes after the 1986 cabinet row which prompted the resignations of
Mr Michael Heseltine and Sir Leon Brittan, then defence and industry
secretaries.
GKN has offered Westland shareholders 290p per ordinary and preferred share,
354.8p for each convertible preferred share and 208.3p for each warrant, all
payable in cash with a partial share alternative.
It also reassured Westland shareholders they would receive a share of any
damages won in its lengthy legal action against the Arab Organisation for
Industrialisation over an alleged breach of contract in 1980.
GKN said the bid would be funded by a one-for-five rights issue of
non-interest bearing convertible loan stock at 490p each in two equal
instalments, the second conditional on 75 per cent acceptance of the bid.
The rights would raise a net Pounds 248m, while the balance of Pounds 118m
would be financed from its own resources. GKN shares closed up 2p at 582p.
Although the 290p price represented a discount on Westland's 307p closing
price yesterday, Sir David said: 'The offer is a fair one', representing a 7
per cent premium on the average share price in January.
UTC, which has opted to take Pounds 75m in cash for its stake, said existing
licensing agreements to build Sikorsky Black Hawk and Sea King helicopters
at Yeovil would be unaffected by the deal.
Sir David warned that GKN's pre-tax profits were expected to decline by more
than 20 per cent to Pounds 97m in the year ended last December 31. It would
pay an unchanged dividend.
