<HEADLINE>
FT  08 FEB 94 / London Stock Exchange: Far East sell-off hits HSBC
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER PRICE, PETER JOHN and JOEL KIBAZO
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The near 10 per cent slide in the Hong Kong stock market sent related shares
in London tumbling on very high volumes as cash flooded out of the Far
Eastern markets and into the US to take advantage of higher interest rates.
The Hang Seng Index fell more then 6 per cent in official trading and 3 per
cent during London trading hours. In the UK, HSBC was the biggest casualty
in the FT-SE 100, losing 83 to 1016p in the London registered with turnover
hitting 15m, and 80 to 1037p in the Hong Kong registered on volume of 4.6m.
Meanwhile, Standard Chartered plummeted 51 to 1380p.
Caution increased as traders discovered that Nomura, the Japanese brokerage,
had cut its recommended weighting of Hong Kong stocks in its global equity
portfolio to zero from 3 per cent.
