<HEADLINE>
FT  08 FEB 94 / London Stock Exchange: Equity futures and options trading
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOEL KIBAZO
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The derivatives sector saw one of its busiest days in recent sessions, with
large turnover in both the Footsie futures and traded options as a firm Wall
Street opening brought a turnround in the market, writes Joel Kibazo.
The much feared early morning crash failed to materialise and the March
futures contract on the FT-SE 100 opened at a reasonably controlled 3,403,
just a five-point discount to cash. Strong selling across the board, led by
the big institutions, saw March fall further, but this settled into two-way
business in late morning trading.
The anticipation, and later confirmation, of a strong performance in New
York early yesterday helped March move firmly ahead and it finished at
3,413, a five-point discount to cash, following very heavy volume of 32,573
lots by the official close.
A hectic session in the traded options brought hefty turnover of 66,805
contracts, of which 31,597 were dealt in the FT-SE 100 option and 8,716 in
the Euro FT-SE 100 option.
Hanson led the league table among the stock options with a total of 2,556
lots dealt and was followed by HSBC at 2,264 trades.
The new OMLX exchange dealing in the FT-SE Mid 250 Index futures and traded
options had a poor day. . Having opened at 4,080, the March futures closed
20 ahead at 4,100 with volume a mere 272 contracts by its 6pm close.
</TEXT>
