<HEADLINE>
FT  08 FEB 94 / International Company News: Peabody raises stake in NSW coal
project
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NIKKI TAIT
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   SYDNEY
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Peabody Resources, part of the British Hanson group, yesterday announced
that it has raised its stake in the Warkworth coal joint venture in New
South Wales, from 28.75 per cent to 43.75 per cent.
The original Warkworth interest was acquired by Peabody when it purchased
the Australian coal mining interests of Costain, the British construction
group, last year for about USDollars 200m.
The joint venture controls around 234m tonnes of recoverable opencast coal
reserves and sizeable underground reserves in New South Wales. It produces
2.8m tonnes a year of metallurgical and steaming coal, mainly for export to
Pacific Rim customers.
Peabody, which is the manager of the Warkworth operation, bought its
additional stake from the Westpac staff superannuation plan, and both sides
declined to disclose the price. Other partners in the joint venture include
Mitsubishi Development, Mitsubishi Materials, Minproc Energy and Nippon
Steel.
The increased interest comes hard on the heels of an unfavourable outcome
for the coal industry in its annual negotiations with the Japanese steel
mills.
Under competitive pressure from other suppliers and faced with lower demand
from Japan, Australian producers accepted larger-than-expected price cuts
and reduced tonnages. A series of 24-hour mine stoppages, called by the
United Mine Workers' union in protest at the outcome of the negotiations, is
due to start tonight.
