<HEADLINE>
FT  08 FEB 94 / UK Company News: Dalgety held back by fall in Pot Noodles
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MAGGIE URRY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Falling sales of Pot Noodles and low pig prices held back interim results at
Dalgety, the food and agribusiness group. Pre-tax profits were slightly
ahead at Pounds 56.4m, against Pounds 56.2m, in the six months to December
31.
Mr Richard Clothier, the new chief executive, said he expected improvement
in many areas in the second half. This was underlined by an increase in the
interim dividend from 7.85p to 8p, in spite of a 7 per cent fall in earnings
per share to 17.2p (18.5p). The shares fell 3p to 487p, holding up against
the market.
The consumer foods division was affected by the supermarket price war but
not severely, according to Mr Clothier, as only half the division's business
was with the UK multiple retailers. The division's trading profits fell 10
per cent to Pounds 27.5m, with acquisitions contributing Pounds 200,000. A
cut in crisp prices at Golden Wonder had been largely recouped through
higher volumes and market share.
Food ingredients profits rose 21 per cent to Pounds 10.9m (Pounds 9.0m),
with Pounds 1.1m of the gain from acquisitions.
Food distribution profits were 16 per cent up at Pounds 8.1m, helped by
exchange rates, and agribusiness profits were 3 per cent ahead at Pounds
15m, thanks to a Pounds 1.4m contribution from acquisitions.
In total, acquisitions added Pounds 1.8m after associated finance costs of
Pounds 1m - which offset a Pounds 900,000 reduction from lower interest
rates. Together with Pounds 1.1m from the fall in sterling against the
dollar and a saving of Pounds 600,000 from the sale of Federal Bakeries, the
gains slightly exceeded a Pounds 4.2m reduction in trading profits on a
comparable basis. Of this reduction about Pounds 2m was due to Pot snacks -
whose figures compared with a strong period when new product launches had
boosted volumes - and about Pounds 1m to low pig prices.
Mr John Martyn, finance director, said Pounds 80m spent on acquisitions,
higher working capital and investment led to a Pounds 99m rise in net debt
to Pounds 208m. With a Pounds 50m goodwill write-off, this lifted gearing to
54 per cent. Mr Martyn said this should fall to around 36-38 per cent by the
year-end. The tax charge rose from 25 to 30 per cent as the group's surplus
ACT was dwindling and profits rose in the higher tax rate areas.
Lex, Page 22
</TEXT>
