<HEADLINE>
FT  08 FEB 94 / International Company News: Woodchester shares fall 30p on
profits warning
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By TIM COONE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   DUBLIN
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Shares in Woodchester Investments, the Dublin-based leasing and banking
group, tumbled 30p to 128p yesterday following a profits warning from the
company as a result of restructuring costs in the UK and Ireland amounting
to IPounds 15m (Pounds 14.4m).
The company reported a 6 per cent drop in pre-tax profits to IPounds 16.4m
in the first half of 1993, and said pre-tax profits for the second half, and
before the new exceptional item, 'will be broadly in line' with that.
Woodchester said the provisions were 'deemed to be fully adequate and are of
a one-off nature.' They are necessary to reduce 'an unacceptably high cost
base' and to eliminate a number of 'peripheral product lines which are
unprofitable.' The restructuring would result in a 'significant improvement'
in the company's long-term profitability.
Credit Lyonnais, Woodchester's majority shareholder, 'has fully endorsed the
restructuring plan . . . and has formally reaffirmed its full commitment to
the continued development of the group.'
At end-1993 NCB stockbrokers in Dublin forecast full-year pre-tax profits of
IPounds 37.5m.
