<HEADLINE>
FT  08 FEB 94 / UK Company News: Bryant pleases City with surge to Pounds
14.6m
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW TAYLOR, Construction Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Profits of Bryant Group, the Midlands-based housebuilder, jumped 95 per cent
to Pounds 14.6m pre-tax during the six months to end-November.
The better than expected return prompted a 5p rise in the share price to
191p on a day when most other share prices were falling.
Mr Andrew MacKenzie, chief executive, said the improvement was due mainly to
a strong performance from housebuilding which increased operating profits by
55 per cent to Pounds 13.5m (Pounds 8.7m).
The interim figures were also helped by a Pounds 300,000 return to profits
from associated residential and commercial property operations. In the
corresponding half year these had incurred a Pounds 1.9m deficit.
Interest payments declined from Pounds 900,000 to Pounds 400,000.
The interim dividend is maintained at 1.4p from earnings per share of 3.6p
(1.9p).
Group turnover increased from Pounds 138.4m to Pounds 178.2m. The number of
homes sold increased from 1,290 to 1,480. Average prices rose from Pounds
81,000 to Pounds 94,000 as the group reduced production of one and two
bedroom homes to concentrate on higher margin large homes.
The mainspring of the profits improvement came in southern England where the
group built some 600 homes and moved from a loss of about Pounds 2m to an
operating profit of about the same amount.
Mr MacKenzie said the group had used up most of the zero and low margin land
it had acquired expensively in southern England during the late 1980s.
The Midlands market, where the group also built about 600 homes, remained
good, producing operating margins in excess of 15 per cent. The north of
England generated reasonable profits after initial start-up costs.
Bryant expects to sell more than 3,000 homes in the current year, compared
with 2,815 in 1992-93.
It anticipated that it would be building more than 4,000 homes a year by
1996.
Construction profits improved from Pounds 2.2m to Pounds 3.1m, helped by the
timing of payments on successful claims rather than any general improvement
in contracting.
Commercial property activities fared less well with operating losses
increasing from Pounds 600,000 to Pounds 1.9m after provisions of Pounds 2m
against some commercial properties.
COMMENT
The market was rightly pleased with Bryant's first half performance. The
switch to higher margin properties should continue to benefit while the
geographical expansion is paying dividends. The high cost of the land bank -
at an average Pounds 25,000 a plot (land acquired since the year end has
cost Pounds 33,000 a plot) - may cause some eyebrows to rise but is
justified, says Bryant, compared with an average selling price in 1994
expected to be at least Pounds 100,000 a home. Gearing currently is about 25
per cent, compared with 3 per cent at the half year, but the balance sheet
can afford it. Pre-tax profits of Pounds 32m would put the company on a
prospective p/e of more than 20. Pre-tax profits of Pounds 42m in 1994-95
would still leave the group on a multiple in the late teens. This rating may
be justified but seems unlikely to rise much further with most of the good
news already in the share price.
