<HEADLINE>
FT  08 FEB 94 / John Sculley quits Spectrum and starts legal action
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LOUISE KEHOE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   SAN FRANCISCO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Mr John Sculley, who last year was ousted from Apple Computer, yesterday
resigned as chairman and chief executive of Spectrum Information
Technologies, the small wireless data communications technology company he
joined in October.
'Certain aspects of Spectrum's business are not what they were represented
to be when I joined the company,' Mr Sculley said yesterday. In a Dollars
10m (Pounds 6.6m) lawsuit filed against Mr Peter Caserta, president of
Spectrum, Mr Sculley charged that he was induced to join the company by
'fraudulent misrepresentation and omissions regarding Spectrum's financial
affairs, legal and regulatory prob lems and its technical and human
resources'.
Mr Sculley's move to Spectrum, four days after he resigned as Apple's
chairman, shocked observers. He had sought the top post at IBM earlier last
year and was a potential candidate for chairman of Eastman Kodak. Instead,
he chose Spectrum, a Dollars 100m little-known New York state company that
has not reported a profit in its 10-year life and has a history of disputes
with investors and competitors. Spectrum's stock price soared 46 per cent on
Mr Sculley's appointment to Dollars 11.50. According to Mr Sculley's
lawsuit, Mr Caserta and other Spectrum officials then made huge profits on
their stock options. Mr Sculley, granted extensive stock options when he
joined Spectrum, stood to make a paper profit of Dollars 73m. Mr Sculley
said he had not exercised any of his stock options, and had surrendered all
options to acquire Spectrum stock. Yesterday Spectrum's stock plummeted to
Dollars before closing at Dollars 2 1/4 , down from Friday's close of
Dollars 5 9/16 .
Mr Sculley charges he was not informed by Mr Caserta that the company was
under investigation by the Securities and Exchange Commission and he was
deliberately misinformed about the company's accounting practices.
But Spectrum claims that 'prior to and during his term at Spectrum, Mr
Sculley was fully aware of the circumstances he now cites as his reasons for
departing'.
Spectrum further alleges that Mr Sculley's resignation 'is clearly in
violation of his employment agreement. . . and disregards his
responsibilities to its (Spectrum) shareholders'.
</TEXT>
