<HEADLINE>
FT  08 FEB 94 / Granada-LWT talks break down over bid price
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RAYMOND SNODDY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Talks aimed at agreeing an improved offer by Granada Group for London
Weekend Television broke down last night, with sources close to Granada
accusing LWT of being 'totally unrealistic about price'.
This will prompt speculation in the London market that Granada will have to
raise its hostile bid - a six-for-five share offer, now worth about Pounds
700m, with a 528p-a-share cash alternative.
The talks were the first since Granada launched its hostile takeover bid two
months ago.
The sides had always seemed far apart, with some LWT executives suggesting
privately that a 200p a share increase could be needed.
Mr Gerry Robinson, chief executive of Granada, the rental, television and
leisure group, had sought the exploratory discussions with Sir Christopher
Bland, the LWT chairman. He was seeking clues on what it would take to reach
an agreement.
Granada first approached LWT over the weekend, but Sir Christopher did not
want to meet until after his final circular to shareholders went out on
Sunday. The talks were expected to explore whether there was any possibility
of persuading the LWT management, which owns 10 per cent of the company, to
recommend a Granada takeover.
Mr Robinson has until Sunday to improve the bid or declare it final.
Yesterday LWT's share price held up better than Granada's, which fell 16p to
570p. LWT was unchanged at 705p.
The issue has to be resolved by February 27 following the clearance of the
Granada bid by the Department of Trade and Industry. The main condition is
that combined advertising sales should account for no more than 25 per cent
of total television advertising.
