<HEADLINE>
FT  08 FEB 94 / ICI agrees Pounds 60m sale to BASF
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DANIEL GREEN and CHRIS TIGHE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BASF has agreed to pay about Pounds 60m for ICI's polypropylene
manufacturing operations, more than a year after the sale was proposed.
The deal marks the UK chemicals company's exit from European polypropylene
manufacture and the German group's elevation from seventh to second biggest
producer in Europe.
The businesses, scheduled to be transferred on March 1, include plants at
Rozenburg, Netherlands, and Wilton, in Teesside in the UK. Some 460 workers
will be transferred.
For ICI, the sale is part of a strategy to concentrate on businesses in
which it has a strong global presence. As only the eighth biggest producer
in Europe, with annual losses of about Pounds 20m, polypropylene was ripe
for disposal.
Nevertheless, the conclusion of the sale is only a partial success. ICI had
wanted to swap the operations for BASF's acrylics business. That foundered
in November when the two sides could not agree a price.
Mr John Newbold, Teesside district secretary of the Transport and General
Workers' Union, the dominant union at ICI's Teesside plants, welcomed the
sale. 'Transition to BASF is the best possible move,' he said.
</TEXT>
