<HEADLINE>
FT  08 FEB 94 / Rise in consumer borrowing but retail sales show decline
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GRAHAM BOWLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The upward trend in consumer borrowing was boosted further in December,
suggesting that the tax increases set out in Mr Kenneth Clarke's first
Budget had little early impact on demand.
Lending to consumers by finance houses, through unsecured loans from
building societies and through bank credit cards under the Visa and
Mastercard systems rose by a net seasonally adjusted Pounds 443m in the
month, up from Pounds 290m in November.
The Central Statistical Office said that, apart from a high September
figure, December's rise was the strongest since January 1990. New credit
advanced to consumers in December was Pounds 4.98bn, just Pounds 4m more
than in November, but a record monthly high. Finance houses boosted their
net lending to Pounds 398m in December, the highest figure for five years,
as spending on vehicles and consumer durables grew. There were small
increases in net lending by building societies and on bank credit cards.
Analysts were surprised by the strength of consumer borrowing. The City
expected a net lending figure nearer Pounds 290m. The rise was in the face
of a disappointing drop in retail sales of 0.2 per cent in December, but
most analysts believe the trend is still upwards.
Other figures published yesterday added to the picture of continued economic
growth. Housing starts rose by a seasonally adjusted 7.7 per cent in the
three months to December over the previous three months. A survey by the
accountancy firm Touche Ross showed that business failures in January were
at their lowest level since December 1989.
The Treasury said the credit figures were consistent with the upward trend
in consumer spending over the past year and a half. Officials said net
lending in the three months to December was at levels last seen before the
recession. In the three months to December, net lending rose to Pounds
1.05bn from Pounds 919m in the previous three months.
However, more comprehensive net lending figures, which include bank
overdrafts and personal loans, showed a drop in the fourth quarter of 1993
to Pounds 634m from Pounds 714m previously.
Home starts at highest since 1989, Page 14
Editorial Comment, Page 21
