<HEADLINE>
FT  08 FEB 94 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER DUNKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Yet again the evening's main offers are current affairs programmes largely
concerned with man's inhumanity to man. Assignment reports on Benazir Bhutto
in Pakistan who faces political and sexual prejudice (7.45 BBC2). In
Undercover Britain two Aids sufferers use hidden cameras to expose con-men
preying on the terminally ill (9.00 C4). 40 Minutes illustrates the
difficulties faced by four former soldiers in finding jobs. Network First
tells of racial segregation in the US Air Force during World War 2 (10.40
ITV).
Where to go for relief? How Do They Do That? on BBC1 is a new 'infotainment'
programme presented by Desmond Lynam which is intended to elicit 'Well would
you believe it' responses (8.00). Food And Drink is usually good for a
giggle, if only for Jilly Goolden's frocks which are as refreshing as her
wine taster's adjectives (8.30 BBC2). And Quantum Leap is one of those
fantasy series which, contrary to popular mythology (Americans are only good
at knock-down drag-out action drama) are better done in the US than in the
UK (9.00 BBC2).
</TEXT>
