<HEADLINE>
FT  08 FEB 94 / Tractors draw David Brown back
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IAN HAMILTON FAZEY, Northern Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The David Brown engineering group has gone back into the tractor business
after an absence of more than 15 years.
The company is making transaxles - combined axles and transmissions - in a
high-technology centre in South Yorkshire.
The first phase of the centre, which will officially open next week at
Penistone, near Barnsley, is making transaxles for the US, German and
Italian tractor markets.
David Brown has invested Pounds 6m refurbishing and equipping a derelict
factory. Mr Roger Bailey, manufacturing director of David Brown vehicle
products, said a Pounds 5m expansion of the site was planned, with up to 160
new jobs in the next two years.
The company has started making transaxles for Agco, the US tractor
manufacturer. David Brown's design has enabled Agco to increase its
tractors' performance from 195hp to 215hp by using high-precision bevelled
gears.
Mr Bailey said coal-mine closures in the region had ensured a supply of
skilled workers who could be retrained for high-precision engineering. The
65 employees have agreed a single-union deal with flexibility to allow
unfettered use of the latest production management systems.
David Brown, which is based in Huddersfield, West Yorkshire, was originally
a private family business famous for its ownership of Aston Martin cars. The
company was floated last April.
</TEXT>
