<HEADLINE>
FT  08 FEB 94 / Farms 'fit for heroes' under threat: Council smallholdings
may fall victim to a budget squeeze
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON MAITLAND
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Henry Duncalfe began farming five years ago on a modest 60 acres near
Wisbech in Cambridgeshire. Today he runs a thriving business growing soft
fruit for Marks and Spencer and Tesco.
He is about to double his acreage to 240, providing summer jobs for 120
fruit-pickers and putting Pounds 130,000 into the depressed local economy.
Mr Duncalfe, a former farm manager, was only able to start his own business
thanks to a little-known institution - the county council small-holding.
He could not afford the price of land and was unable to find a long-term
tenancy in the private sector because fears about security of tenure have
stopped landowners letting for more than a few years.
Now the 5,700 public-sector farms in England and Wales are under threat from
local government reorganisation and the squeeze on council budgets.
Many in the industry are worried that the farms, promoted by Lloyd George to
provide 'land fit for heroes' returning from the first world war, will be
split up and sold off.
The pressure on councils to realise short-term capital gains is mounting. Mr
Desmond Hampton of land agents Cluttons told a recent conference organised
by the Royal Institution of Chartered Surveyors: 'If I was advising county
councils, I would be suggesting they should retain their estate until they
can secure vacant possession of any holding, but at that point sell it to
the best advantage in the open market.'
The case was strengthened by 'the small and frequently uneconomic size of
the county council farming unit'.
Mr Greg Birdseye of the Audit Commission said county councils had to ask
'whether there might be better things to do with the money' given
agricultural over-production and the squeeze on other services such as
education.
Advocates of the county farm system believe such arguments are misplaced.
Mr Charles Coats, head of Gloucestershire Estates Consultancy, which runs
9,000 acres of farms, says the farms bring jobs, new ideas and environmental
benefits such as public access and maintained hedgerows.
The Gloucestershire estate employs 480 people directly and indirectly -
which suggests more than 18,000 jobs on the 340,000 acres of council farms
nationally.
Demand for tenancies is strong. Gloucestershire receives 20 to 30
applications for each of the four or five vacancies that arise every year.
Competition has been intensified by a logjam. County farms were designed to
give young entrants a first step on the farming ladder.
But many tenants have failed to move on because there are no long-term
private-sector tenancies - a problem which should be eased by pending
de-regulation.
Tenants also had life tenure until retirement at 65 was introduced in 1984.
Farmers pay commercial rents but they benefit from 'pump-priming' in the
form of loans for repairs or new buildings and machinery which they pay back
through rent increases.
The county councils also bear the extra costs of managing a large number of
small farms of 100 acres or less which private landowners would generally
amalgamate.
But council farms are 'not a drain on the taxpayer', insists Mr Coats.
He says most estates produce surpluses on both revenue and capital through
careful management and sales of unwanted land and buildings for development.
And he believes that the break-up of county councils into unitary
authorities could reverse those gains.
The local government commissioners have recommended keeping the status quo
in Gloucestershire, but neighbouring counties such as Somerset face big
reorganisation.
'Our concern is that if there's a split into smaller authorities . . . one
could lose the economies of scale and of managing on a county-wide basis,'
says Mr Coats.
Some farmers' leaders are suggesting keeping estates intact by having them
transferred into trusts.
They might be managed under contract by existing teams acting as
private-sector consultants - an option Mr Duncalfe would favour if, as seems
likely, Cambridgeshire County Council is split up.
Success stories like Mr Duncalfe's are being used by proponents of the
county farms to press for their preservation.
'If we don't provide this service, there aren't the opportunities for the
able, entrepreneurial and innovative to start in farming,' said Mr Coats.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P0762 Farm Management Services.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
<TP>CMMT  Comment &amp; Analysis.
</TP>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
