<HEADLINE>
FT  08 FEB 94 / Tory minister defends quangos
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JAMES BUXTON, Scottish Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The claim that the creation of quangos represented centralisation in
government was 'preposterous' and the idea that they were unaccountable was
'absurd', Mr Ian Lang, Scottish secretary, said yesterday.
He said quangos were an effective way of devolving responsibility for
achieving policy objectives. They were not 'poodles in the lap of the
secretary of state'.
Mr Lang's speech in Edinburgh, on the theme of 'reinventing government',
followed a Labour onslaught on quangos, or quasi autonomous non-governmental
organisations. At the weekend Mr John Smith, the Labour leader, said they
were an abuse of democratic rights.
Mr Henry McLeish, Labour MP for Fife, said in the Commons yesterday: 'We see
a situation where the public interest is playing second fiddle to private
and vested interests. The promotion of the culture of closet Toryism is well
to the fore. Nearly 5,000 people . . . are spending nearly Pounds 7bn of
public money.'
These bodies had 'very tenuous' lines of accountability to the Scottish
Office, parliament, the press, MPs and the public, he said.
Mr Lang said quangos such as school boards and health trusts in Scotland
were examples of the 'exact opposite of centralisation' and were designed to
carry the devolutionary process to the grass roots. They had many
representatives of other political parties and 'still more of none,' he
said.
Quangos were accountable to parliament through their sponsoring secretary of
state, with chief executives responsible to the accounting officer in the
relevant government department. Mr Lang said quangos had a vested interest
in securing policy success in a way that 'could not, perhaps, be expected of
officials working in seemingly amorphous government departments'.
The Conservatives had cut the number of quangos in Scotland by almost half
since a 1980 report identified 84 executive public bodies, many of them
created by Labour.
Mr George Robertson, Labour's shadow Scottish secretary, said that the
government's planned reform of local government would reduce the number of
elected councillors compared with non-elected quango members.
</TEXT>
