<HEADLINE>
FT  08 FEB 94 / Insolvency Service commission
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD LAPPER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The government is to commission new work examining the feasibility of
handing parts of the work of the Insolvency Service to the private sector,
Richard Lapper writes.
The announcement follows the completion late last year of a study by Stoy
Hayward, the accountants. It concluded that the private sector could handle
most of the mechanical processing of bankruptcy and compulsory liquidations
work, leaving the official receivers to concentrate on their investigative
role.
In answer to a parliamentary question, Mr Neil Hamilton, the minister for
corporate affairs, said that Stoy Hayward's findings 'provide a sufficient
basis for further, more detailed work'. If the work reveals 'likely
value-for-money gains' the government will consider the possibility of 'live
trials in one or more regions'.
It is expected that the government will appoint consultants to carry out the
new work before the end of the month.
</TEXT>
