<HEADLINE>
FT  08 FEB 94 / Howard abolishes committal court hearings
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT RICE, Legal Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Magistrates' court committal hearings at which prosecution evidence is
reviewed to see if a case is strong enough to go to trial at the Crown
Court, are to be abolished, Mr Michael Howard, the home secretary, announced
yesterday.
The hearings, most of which are a formality, are to be replaced by an
administrative procedure which would save money, reduce stress on victims
and witnesses and cut delays in bringing cases to trial, he said.
A clause inserted into the Criminal Justice and Public Order bill will still
allow for the defence to argue there is no case to answer.
This argument will be put to magistrates in writing. The defence will also
be able to apply for an oral hearing, but not to call witnesses.
The change will affect about 9,000 full committal hearings a year at which
witnesses give evidence, and a further 120,000 'paper' committals at which
magistrates commit defendants for trial solely on the basis of written
statements.
Responding to a parliamentary question from Sir Ivan Lawrence, chairman of
the home affairs select committee, Mr Howard said: 'These changes will
reduce the pressure on vulnerable witnesses by ensuring they will no longer
be at risk of having to give evidence twice.
'They will also produce significant savings in court time and costs.'
The proposal, which follows procedural changes in fraud cases and hearings
involving evidence from children, will apply to all charges to be tried at
the Crown Court. The change was recommended by the Royal Commission on
Criminal Justice which reported last July.
The commission concluded that the present system served no useful purpose.
Defendants should still be able to make a submission of no case to answer,
the commission said, but witnesses should not be called and thereby made to
give their evidence twice over.
</TEXT>
