<HEADLINE>
FT  08 FEB 94 / Heads 'lose out' on pay awards
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LISA WOOD, Labour Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Many school governing bodies are too embarrassed to give discretionary
awards to head teachers and their deputies, according to a report by the
Institute of Manpower Studies.
The report, based on a survey of 1,600 heads and deputies, estimates that
senior staff in almost two-thirds of schools in England and Wales went for
more than a year without a formal salary review.
Discretionary additions to national awards can be made for a number of
reasons, including overall performance and levels of responsibility.
Mr John Stock, co-author of the report, said: 'It seems that many governing
bodies find discussing the pay of their head embarrassing and demeaning -
which means that many heads and deputies lose out.'
Some respondents said governors had no understanding of what was involved in
the job and no experience of pay determination.
Mr Stock said the recommendation of annual review by a standing committee of
governors, made last week by the school teachers review body, should help
clarify the process.
Specialists charged with slimming down the national curriculum have not cut
enough, the government Schools Curriculum and Assessment Authority said
yesterday.
Sir Ron Dearing, its chairman, announced last month that substantial cuts
were to be made in the prescribed curriculum for schools in England and
Wales, so that 20 per cent of classroom time could be left to teachers'
discretion.
But Mr Chris Woodhead, chief executive of the authority, said plans
submitted by subject working groups had not been sufficiently ruthless.
Separate working groups have returned the draft proposals to subject
specialists for further cuts.
A head for figures? A survey of head and deputy head teachers. IMS Report
262 1994 Pounds 35. From BEBC, PO Box 1496, Parkstone, Poole, Dorset BH1
23YD.
</TEXT>
