<HEADLINE>
FT  08 FEB 94 / New tax to fund NHS proposed
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALAN PIKE, Social Affairs Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Financing the National Health Service through an earmarked tax rather than
general taxation could prove popular and clarify the debate on NHS
expenditure, the British Medical Association says in a discussion document
published yesterday.
The BMA paper argues that a 'hypothecated', or dedicated, tax would
encourage public discussion about investment in the NHS, and could under
some circumstances lead to greater funding. It recognises, however, that the
Treasury would probably oppose a specific health tax, although 'its
objections are likely to be based more on political than economic
judgments'.
Yesterday's paper is the first in a series of research and discussion
documents that the BMA plans to publish to encourage debate on health policy
issues. Other subjects will include the democratic accountability of NHS
purchasing authorities, equality of access to health services and community
care.
The BMA has consistently argued that the NHS is underfunded and one of the
potential attractions of financing the service through a dedicated tax is
health's relative popularity with the public as a spending priority.
But the document acknowledges the difficulties that would be involved in
introducing such a system. An independent body would, it says, be needed to
oversee funds raised by the health tax and determine the expenditure and tax
rates required.
There would be likely to be political opposition to setting up a body with
power to recommend changes in taxation that could have a considerable impact
on the management of the economy.
A specific health tax could, suggests the BMA document, take one of several
forms. The widest coverage of potential taxpayers would be achieved by a
flat rate or graduated health tax. But, by representing proportionately more
of the income of lower earners, it could run into the same problems as the
community charge.
The Labour party is to publish a consultative document on its future health
policy shortly. This may allow scope for debate on the possibility of a
hypothecated health tax.
Hypothecated Tax Funding for the NHS. British Medical Association, BMA
House, Tavistock Square London WC1H 9JP. Free.
</TEXT>
