<HEADLINE>
FT  08 FEB 94 / Pollution burden on shipping grows
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD LAPPER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The cost of pollution is becoming a financial burden for shipowners,
according to a study by the UK Protection &amp; Indemnity Club, which covers
liabilities for the owners and charterers of 8,000 ships, about 25 per cent
of the world's ocean-going fleet.
Pollution claims have amounted to Dollars 132m (Pounds 88m) since 1987, with
more than 114 claims costing Dollars 1.2m on average. During 1992, the last
year for which figures are available, the number of pollution claims
reported to the club increased to 35, compared with 79 over the previous
five years.
'Pollution tends to be an all-or-nothing claim,' said Mr Peter Donnellan, a
director of Thomas Miller P &amp; I, which manages the club.
'It is increasingly expensive for all shipowners. We have to make the
mariner aware that even the smallest spillages of fuel oil can be very
damaging for the environment,' he added.
Tankers are involved in 45 per cent of pollution claims, according to the
club's latest analysis of claims. But about one-third resulted from spills
of fuel oil, many of which were the result of human error.
Overall between 1987 and 1992 the club's managers paid Dollars 989m in
meeting 1,971 separate claims, according to the analysis. In the course of
1982 527 claims were reported costing members Dollars 205m.
Cargo and personal injury claims accounted for about three-quarters of total
claims. The steady increase in claims has led to a tripling in premium rates
since 1987.
</TEXT>
