FT  08 FEB 94 / Whips lobby Tory MPs to back de-regulation move
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROLAND RUDD
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The government's business managers have been lobbying Tory backbenchers to
support its de-regulation initiative which seeks to give parliament sweeping
new powers.
On the eve of the bill's second reading a Tory whip said the government
could have a difficult time overturning any Lords amendment watering down
the bill, which would give ministers the power to amend or repeal laws
without primary legislation.
The whip said: 'Any attempt to amend this bill would destroy the initiative.
There cannot be any U-turn.'
Mrs Angela Rumbold MP, a strong supporter of the bill, conceded that a
number of Tory backbenchers would need reassurances.
She said: 'This bill does not go far enough quickly enough but it is a very
important start.'
Mr Robin Cook, shadow trade and industry secretary, attacked the bill for
trying to repeal primary legislation without going through the 'proper
procedures'.
The Institute of Directors called on MPs to reject any amendments to bills
limiting the order-making powers proposed for ministers.
Ms Ann Robinson, the institute's head of policy, said: 'It is ridiculous to
argue about constitutional concerns. The fact is the constitutional balance
as it stands is tipped in favour of regulation.'
Ministers argue that the key to the bill is the powers it gives government
to repeal regulation 'on an ongoing basis'.
The Department of Trade and Industry yesterday moved to make some of the
banking accounting requirements of the Companies Act 1985 more flexible. The
move, part of the de-regulation drive, will remove the definition of
'banking activities' and 'banking transactions' in one of the schedules to
the act.
