<HEADLINE>
FT  08 FEB 94 / Talks on paper's future to be held
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RAYMOND SNODDY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Ian Hay Davison, chairman of Newspaper Publishing which owns The
Independent newspaper, will hold talks in the next few days with all those
involved in the loss-making company's future.
Mr Hay Davison, accompanied by Sir Kit McMahon, a fellow non-executive
director, will meet the main parties in turn to try to gauge their
intentions.
Those involved include the founders' group, led by Mr Andreas Whittam Smith,
which controls 10 per cent of the company; the two continental European
newspaper groups El Pas of Spain and La Repubblica of Italy which together
own 37 per cent; and Mr Tony O'Reilly, chairman of Independent Newspapers of
Ireland, who bought a 24.99 per cent stake in Newspaper Publishing on
Friday.
The two non-executive directors will also meet Mr David Montgomery, chief
executive of Mirror Group Newspapers, which would have taken a 40 per cent
stake in Newspaper Publishing if a Pounds 55m bid for the company had
succeeded.
The consortium which groups MGN, El Pas, La Repubblica and the founders is
now considering the possibility of an increased offer for the company
although it is believed that no final decision has yet been taken.
Meanwhile, it is believed that contacts have continued between Mr Hay
Davison and Lord Hollick's MAI group which recently made an agreed takeover
bid for Anglia Television. Mr Hay Davison believes that persuading a
television company to become a minority shareholder would help protect the
group's independence.
