<HEADLINE>
FT  08 FEB 94 / Review of counties' future extended
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
More time is to be allowed for the first stages of most of the review of
local government in the English counties, the Local Government Commission
for England decided yesterday.
The decision follows the the government's announcement that it would not
appeal against the recent High Court ruling that Mr John Gummer, the
environment secretary, had acted unlawfully in calling for the two-tier
structure of county and district councils to be abandoned in all but
'exceptional' circumstances.
The government said some councils had asked the commission for more time to
consider their positions because they felt the change of guidance might
alter the nature of the submissions they were planning to send to the
commission.
The commission is to allow those scheduled to submit proposals at the end of
February and at the end of March more time - an extra six weeks and an extra
five weeks respectively. But because those due to make their proposals at
the end of April and the end of May will have enough time to consider their
position, it does not propose to alter these dates.
Mr Gummer has already approved the commission's final recommendations for
the creation of a unitary council on the Isle of Wight and of four unitary
councils for Cleveland. He has asked it to review Derbyshire and County
Durham again.
The commission said draft recommendations would be produced for consultation
in the late spring or summer.
It believes all reviews are still likely to be completed by the original
deadline of December 31.
</TEXT>
