<HEADLINE>
FT  08 FEB 94 / Broad ban on smoking proposed by US bill
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By REUTER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
The US administration yesterday endorsed a bill to ban or restrict smoking
in virtually all commercial and public buildings because of the health
hazard to non-smokers, especially children, Reuter reports from Washington.
Ms Carol Browner, head of the Environmental Protection Agency, said the
agency 'firmly believes that the scientific evidence is sufficient to
warrant actions to protect non-smokers from involuntary exposure to
second-hand smoke.' She was testifying to a health sub-committee of the
House of Representatives.
Ms Browner emphasised her special concern over 'the very serious respiratory
effects on young children.'
The bill would ban smoking in all non-residential buildings used or visited
by at least 10 people a week, except in specially ventilated smoking areas.
In the case of buildings which lacked such areas, smokers would have to go
outside to light up.
