<HEADLINE>
FT  08 FEB 94 / Peace hopes raised by Arafat and Peres
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JULIAN OZANNE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   CAIRO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Shimon Peres, Israeli foreign minister, and Mr Yassir Arafat, PLO
chairman, last night raised expectations they would complete a long delayed
security agreement on Palestinian self-rule as they began meeting in Cairo.
Both men said they had made progress in the first round of talks at the
Egyptian foreign ministry and that they hoped to reach and initial a final
agreement in Cairo. The two sides were to continue talking overnight and
this morning.
The completion of an agreement, after months of bitter argument between the
two sides, would pave the way for beginning of Israeli troop withdrawal from
the Gaza Strip and West Bank area of Jericho and the transfer of power to
Palestinian hands.
But an agreement has proved elusive and even yesterday, hours before Mr
Peres was due to meet Mr Arafat, the Cairo talks were in doubt as Mr Peres
met senior Israeli army officers in Jerusalem to listen to their
reservations about security concessions to the PLO.
Mr Arafat had threatened not to attend unless he was sure Mr Peres had the
authority to conclude a draft agreement reached between the two men in
Davos, Switzerland, last week.
For the past week, Mr Arafat has reiterated he is ready to sign the Davos
draft agreement which largely resolved the outstanding obstacles between the
two sides on long-delayed implementation of Palestinian self-rule in
Gaza-Jericho, including the most sensitive issues of control over border
crossings and security for Jew ish settlers.
But since the Peres-Arafat meeting, objections have been raised by senior
officials of the Israeli army backed by Mr Yitzhak Rabin, prime minister.
Mr Peres last night sought to reassure Palestinians. He said Israel saw the
agreement as 'a top priority and we should try and conclude it'. He had come
to Cairo with a mandate to conclude negotiations and Israel would stand by
the Davos agreement.
'I am not a private person and whatever we agreed in Davos will be respected
and kept to,' he said.
Mr Amr Moussa, Egyptian foreign minister, said the first round of
Peres-Arafat talks last night had been good and the two sides were not far
apart. It had confirmed both parties were working hard towards a final
agreement. Mr Moussa earlier said 90 per cent of the work had been completed
but the remaining gaps would not be easy.
Israeli officials cautioned that the talks might not produce a signed
agreement unless there was considerable flexibility on Mr Arafat's part to
meet the objections put for ward by the army, particularly over control on
border cross ings and roads between Israel and the settlements in Gaza.
Mr Rabin has recently insisted he will only formally sign a comprehensive
agree ment with Mr Arafat to begin Israeli withdrawal from Gaza- Jericho.
According to Mr Rabin, the comprehensive agreement must include all
outstanding issues between the two sides, including security, the
responsibility of the Pales tinian police force, and the future economic
relations between the two economies.
Officials said if things went well in Cairo, Mr Arafat and Mr Peres might
initial an agreement on security issues, but a formal Rabin-Arafat sign ing
would have to wait a fur ther two to three weeks for economic and other
issues to be finalised in Paris and Taba.
Israeli jets yesterday bombed south Lebanon twice in retaliation for attacks
by pro-Iranian guerrillas which left three Israeli soldiers dead and four
wounded. The attack on Israeli forces in Israel's self-declared security
zone is the bloodiest such raid in six months.
</TEXT>
