<HEADLINE>
FT  08 FEB 94 / S Africa talks hit impasse
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PATTI WALDMEIR
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   JOHANNESBURG
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Talks between the South African government, the African National Congress
and right-wing groups demanding constitutional change broke down last night,
increasing the threat of a violent boycott of April's all-race elections.
The negotiations, which have dragged on for months without success, appeared
to have reached a serious impasse, with no further talks scheduled to take
place before Saturday's deadline for political parties to register for the
elections.
The talks broke down over the issue of the autonomy of regions under South
Africa's interim constitution, with the right-wing Freedom Alliance
demanding that autonomy be protected when the constituent assembly elected
in April sits down to write a final constitution.
ANC negotiator Joe Slovo said unless there was 'serious movement on
fundamental questions on the part of the Freedom Alliance, I would say there
is no hope.'
Last night's talks took place against a background of sabotage attacks
against railways, power lines and ANC offices. Police said there had been
more than 40 such attacks in ultra-conservative areas of the Orange Free
State and western Transvaal since December.
