<HEADLINE>
FT  08 FEB 94 / Jordan's relief
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JAMES WHITTINGTON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   AMMAN
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Jordan has won slight relief on its external debts to Japan following
agreement between the two sides which will add Dollars 14.1m (Pounds 9.4m)
of principal and interest to Dollars 87.3m in debts to Japan which have
already been rescheduled, writes James Whittington in Amman.
This will not affect most of Jordan's Dollars 1.3bn mainly official debt to
Japan, for which repayment will be discussed in the next round talks with
the Paris Club of official creditors in late March.
The terms are the same as for the rescheduled Dollars 87.3m of interest and
principal agreed in June 1992. There is a grace period of nine years for
official loans and seven years for commercial loans backed by the Japanese
government.
Jordan's total external debt is around Dollars 6.8bn, or 140 per cent of
gross domestic product, after Dollars 673m of repayments on principal and
interest in 1993.
</TEXT>
