<HEADLINE>
FT  08 FEB 94 / Poland's PM lets finance minister go
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER BOBINSKI
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WARSAW
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Poland faces a shift away from tight budget policies following the
acceptance by Mr Waldemar Pawlak, prime minister, of his finance minister's
resignation.
Mr Marek Borowski, a member of the Social Democratic party (SLD), offered to
quit last week after failing to win assurances from Mr Pawlak, who heads the
Peasant party (PSL), that co-ordination of economic policy would be improved
within the two-party governing coalition.
Mr Alexander Kwasniewski, the SLD leader, who had been urging Mr Pawlak to
keep Mr Borowski, said yesterday he was 'inclined to look for a compromise',
suggesting that he would not put the four-month-old coalition at risk over
the resignation.
Mr Borowski departs as parliamentary committees debate this year's draft
budget before a final vote later this month. The budget, which assumes a 4.2
per cent deficit in gross domestic product, has already been agreed with the
International Monetary Fund, whose approval is crucial to a decision on
reducing Poland's Dollars 30bn Paris Club debt by 20 per cent at the end of
March.
The present draft budget differs little from that planned by the previous
government led by Ms Hanna Suchocka, whose election defeat last autumn paved
the way for the present coalition.
Mr Pawlak said on television last night that the draft would be modified,
but the changes would 'respect the needs of the economy', implying awareness
of the inflationary dangers of too great a change.
The shift in tone comes as opinion polls are telling the government that its
support is waning, and precedes a large street demonstration planned for
tomorrow by the Solidarity trade union in Warsaw.
</TEXT>
