<HEADLINE>
FT  08 FEB 94 / Stock markets slide but fears of steeper fall are unfounded:
European exchanges stem declines - Far eastern bourses hardest hit
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP COGGAN and PATRICK HARVERSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   LONDON, NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
International stock markets stumbled yesterday as the aftershock of Friday's
rise in short-term US interest rates reverberated around the world.
In London, the FT-SE 100 fell by 93.4 points to 3,382.0 by midday before
eventually closing down 56.3 points at 3,419.1, a drop of 1.6 per cent on
the day. The broader FT-SE 350 index fell 28.8 points to 1,731.7.
Asian stock markets were the worst hit, with Hong Kong dropping 6.1 per cent
and Thailand falling 6.9 per cent.
But fears of a substantial setback proved unfounded, with European equity
markets rallying in the afternoon after a calm opening on Wall Street.
The mood in the markets indicated that yesterday's falls were a one-off
correction. Attention will now focus in the short term on far eastern
markets, with the Hong Kong market falling a further 3 per cent in
indicative trading in London yesterday.
The markets were clearly jittery but traders said there was little sign of
panic. Much of the fall represented a catch-up with the 96 point decline in
the Dow Jones Average on Friday, a large part of which occurred after
European markets had closed.
The timing of the Federal Reserve's move was a surprise, but a rise in US
interest rates had been expected and does not necessarily presage a similar
rise in Europe.
Analysts said there was still scope for European rates to fall, given low
inflation and the relatively depressed European economies. In Frankfurt, the
Dax fell 58.85 points, or 2.75 per cent, to 2,079.4. In Paris, the CAC Index
dropped 42.11 points, or 1.81 per cent, to 2,287.06.
However, analysts pointed to a number of issues which could yet disturb the
markets: the Federal Reserve might increase rates farther and faster than
anticipated; US private investors might redeem some of their substantial
holdings in mutual funds, causing managers to sell equities; or the
Bundesbank might decide not to cut German interest rates, in order to stop
the D-Mark from weakening against the US dollar.
Mr Michael Hughes, managing director, BZW Global Economics and Strategy,
said that the latest changes marked an end to the 'emerging markets bubble'.
He said that markets such as Hong Kong, which had been buoyed by speculative
flows from US investors, might suffer particularly.
US financial markets were restored to relative calm yesterday after Friday's
big losses. Although share prices fluctuated erratically after the opening
bell, by noon the stock market had settled down with dealers reporting
plenty of buying and selling activity but no clear direction.
Later, a series of computerised buy programs pushed stocks, especially those
of big companies such as IBM and Walt Disney firmly higher. By 1pm the Dow
Jones Industrial Average was up 22.23 at 3,893.65.
The US Treasury market was also relatively quiet yesterday morning, although
continued selling of long-term government securities, some of it linked to
this week's auction of Dollars 11bn in new bonds, pushed the benchmark
30-year issue down about half a point, to where it yielded 6.387 per cent.
In Europe, government bonds traded lower, with gilts down around  3/4 of a
point.
In London, the US dollar traded slightly higher against the D-Mark at
DM1.7630 and slightly weaker against the yen at Y108.7050.
Analysts said the Fed interest rate move had been positive for the dollar
but was insufficient to move the US currency any higher until the Bundesbank
indicates the likely direction of German interest rates.
